<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-035-069 </DOCNO><DOCID>11 452 047</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic Engineering Times  Oct 14 1991 n663 p72(5).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Passive components move toward integration: update/resistors andcapacitors. (includes related article on use of Dcap-typecapacitors)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Derman, Glenda.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The functions of passive components, such as capacitors andresistors, are being more highly integrated to address thehigh-speed switching requirements and greater space limitations ofnew generations of electronics equipment.andP;  The worldwide marketfor multilayer ceramic chip capacitors is expected to grow 14percent in 1991, though the US market is stagnant.andP;  The increasedintegration of capacitive functions is propelling the developmentof new thick- and thin-film capacitor devices and capacitivearrays and networks.andP;  Another major trend is the growing US demandfor tantalum chip capacitors because of improvements in electricalperformance.andP;  Trends in resistors include smaller package sizes,tighter electrical parameters, greater use of thick- and thin-filmtechnologies and more complex circuitry.andP;  A variety ofexemplifying capacitors and resistors are briefly described.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     CapacitorsResistorsTrendsIntegrated Circuit FabricationCircuit DesignIntegrated ApproachSizeProductsProduct Development.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotographgraph.andO;Caption:   Capacitance vs volume for various types of capacitors. (graph)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>